{
  "id": "019d3dd8-e934-77b3-a8c8-52a336ce18d1",
  "content": "# Kernel Event Bus -- Design Decisions (2026-03-30)\n\n## What\nIntroduce an in-process event bus (`tokio::broadcast`) to the kernel so subsystems can publish state transitions and observability consumers can subscribe without direct coupling. Ships with two day-one consumers: CLI `corvia watch` and JSONL event logger.\n\n## Key Design Decisions\n\n1. **Hybrid approach (Approach C).** Events layer on top of existing direct calls. Direct calls remain primary control flow. Events are informational and not load-bearing. Chosen over full event bus (Approach A, too risky for ~6 call sites) and callback hooks (Approach B, trait grows with events).\n\n2. **Lean event variants (IDs only).** KernelEvent carries UUIDs and string IDs, not full data structs. Avoids cloning KnowledgeEntry (which includes 768-float embeddings) through broadcast. Consumers look up full data by ID.\n\n3. **Publish AFTER direct calls succeed.** Prevents phantom events for failed operations. Preserves the idempotent crash-recovery model from the commit pipeline.\n\n4. **CancellationToken for shutdown.** Solves the Arc reference cycle problem where MergeWorker's infinite loop holds Arc<EventBus> preventing sender drop. Token gives clean termination signal.\n\n5. **Pipeline middleware deferred.** 5-persona review found existing PipelineTrace + OTel spans already cover retrieval observability. TracingSearcher would duplicate. Middleware ships later when a genuine gap emerges (e.g., CachingSearcher).\n\n6. **Reranker/Augmenter traits kept as-is.** Single implementations (IdentityReranker, StructuredAugmenter) retained for future extensibility. Owner decision.\n\n7. **RBAC stays as early-exit guard, not middleware.** Already well-placed in RetrievalPipeline::retrieve() step 1. Tier weighting stays per-searcher (domain logic, not cross-cutting).\n\n## Relationship to Existing Event Systems\n- `EventBus` (new) = in-process kernel state transitions\n- `SessionWatcherState` = external Claude Code session file-watching (separate concern)\n- `corvia_common::events` = legacy JSONL log, becomes a consumer of EventBus\n\n## Alternatives Rejected\n- Full event bus replacing direct calls (Approach A): too much indirection for ~6 call sites\n- Callback hooks via KernelListener trait (Approach B): trait grows with each event, coupled to coordinator\n- Tower-style generic middleware: type explosion, already using dyn Trait throughout\n- Pipeline-level pre/post hooks: too coarse, cannot wrap individual stages\n\n## Review Process\n5-persona review (Senior SWE, PM, QA, Domain Expert, Developer Experience). PM challenged timing; resolved by adding two concrete day-one consumers (CLI watch + JSONL logger). QA identified shutdown protocol gap. Domain expert validated tokio::broadcast choice. All 5 approved with fixes incorporated.\n\nGitHub issue: chunzhe10/corvia#102",
  "source_version": "mcp",
